\chapter{Introduction}

This document is a literate reverse engineering of \emph{Ultima I: The
First Age of Darkness} for the Apple~II. Every byte of the original
program is reproduced by the assembly chunks herein: tangling this
document and assembling the result yields binaries identical to the
original disk image. The document is written for a reader who wants to
understand how the game was built --- in enough detail to reproduce or
port it in any language, on any platform. Platform-independent
descriptions of the game's design, data structures, and algorithms
accompany the annotated assembly throughout.

\section{The game}

\emph{Ultima} was written by Richard Garriott (``Lord British'') and
published by California Pacific Computer in 1981, the first entry in
what became one of the longest-running role-playing series in computer
gaming. The original was largely Applesoft BASIC. In 1986 Origin
Systems published a complete rewrite in 6502 assembly language for the
Apple~II --- faster, with redrawn graphics --- under the title
\emph{Ultima I: The First Age of Darkness}. That 1986 remake is the
program reverse engineered here. (The disk image is the ``4am crack''
preservation release, which removes only the original disk's copy
protection; the program itself is Origin's. The startup banner in the
binary reads ``Copyright 1986 by Origin Systems, Inc.'')

The player creates a character (race, sex, class, attribute points)
and explores the realm of Sosaria to defeat the evil wizard Mondain.
Play moves between six distinct modes, each with its own presentation:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Outdoors} --- a tile-scrolled overworld map of four
  continents, with towns, castles, and dungeon entrances.
\item \textbf{Towns} --- tile maps with shops (weapons, armour, food,
  magic, pubs) and citizens.
\item \textbf{Castles} --- tile maps where kings give quests and
  rewards.
\item \textbf{Dungeons} --- first-person three-dimensional wireframe
  mazes, ten levels deep, populated by monsters.
\item \textbf{Space} --- a first-person space-flight shooter sequence;
  destroying enemy craft earns the ``space ace'' status the endgame
  requires.
\item \textbf{Time machine} --- the endgame confrontation with
  Mondain, fought in the past.
\end{itemize}

The program is structured exactly along these lines: a memory-resident
engine provides shared services, and one overlay file per mode is
loaded over a common overlay region as the player moves between modes.
This architecture is visible directly in the disk's file listing and
drives the organization of this document.

\section{How the program is organized}

The game runs under ProDOS, Apple's then-current operating system, and
its data lives in ordinary ProDOS files on a volume named
\texttt{/U1}. The boot chain is:

\begin{enumerate}
\item The Disk~II controller PROM loads the 512-byte \textbf{boot
  block} at [[$0800]] and jumps to it.
\item The boot block finds the file \texttt{PRODOS} in the volume
  directory, loads it at [[$2000]], and jumps to it. This file is the
  stock ProDOS~1.1.1 kernel (dated 18-SEP-84), byte-identical to
  Apple's release; it is treated as an external dependency in this
  document, like the monitor ROM.
\item ProDOS relocates itself high, then loads and runs the first
  \texttt{.SYSTEM} file in the directory: \texttt{U1.SYSTEM}, the
  game's launcher.
\item \texttt{U1.SYSTEM} loads and runs \texttt{U1.INTRO} (title and
  main menu), which in turn starts the game proper: the resident
  engine \texttt{MI.U1} at [[$7000]] plus one mode overlay at
  [[$8956]].
\end{enumerate}

\chapter{Disk layout and boot chain}

\section{Disk image format}

The disk image is a 140K \texttt{.dsk} file: 35 tracks of 16 sectors
of 256 bytes, stored in DOS~3.3 logical order. The volume on it,
however, is a ProDOS volume, which addresses the disk in 512-byte
\emph{blocks} (two sectors each, 8 blocks per track, 280 blocks per
volume).

Three sector orderings are therefore in play, and all the extraction
tooling reduces to composing two fixed permutations:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Physical order} --- the order sectors pass under the
  drive head; the order in the sector address fields. The controller
  PROM and the boot code address physical sectors.
\item \textbf{DOS 3.3 logical order} --- the order sectors are stored
  in the \texttt{.dsk} file. Physical sector $P$ of track $T$ is at
  file offset $T \cdot 4096 + \mathit{DOS}[P] \cdot 256$ with
  $$\mathit{DOS} = [0,7,14,6,13,5,12,4,11,3,10,2,9,1,8,15].$$
\item \textbf{ProDOS block order} --- ProDOS block $B$ lives on track
  $\lfloor B/8 \rfloor$; its two halves are ProDOS logical sectors
  $2(B \bmod 8)$ and $2(B \bmod 8)+1$, which map to physical sectors
  through $$\mathit{PRO} = [0,2,4,6,8,10,12,14,1,3,5,7,9,11,13,15].$$
  Note the two halves of a block always sit two physical sectors
  apart --- a fact the boot block's sector reader exploits
  (section~\ref{sec:diskii-read-block}).
\end{itemize}

The script \texttt{.claude/scripts/prodos\_extract.py} implements this
mapping, walks the ProDOS volume directory, and extracts every file
into \texttt{reference/} as the flat reference binaries that all
assembly targets verify against.

