\chapter{Boot block}

The first 512 bytes of the disk --- ProDOS block~0, physical track~0
sectors~0 and~2 --- are Apple's standard ProDOS~1.x boot loader, the
same on every ProDOS-formatted disk of the era. It is included here in
full because it is part of the byte-exact reproduction, and because it
is a beautifully compact piece of code: in half a kilobyte it boots
two different machines (Apple~II and Apple~///), drives the Disk~II
stepper motor, reads sectors by borrowing and patching the
controller's own PROM code, parses the ProDOS volume directory, and
loads a file by walking its index block.

The PROM loads the first half at [[$0800]]--[[$08FF]] and jumps to
[[BOOT_ENTRY]]. Execution proceeds in five phases:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Re-enter the PROM to fetch the block's second half to
  [[$0900]]--[[$09FF]].
\item Build a standalone sector-read routine by copying the
  controller's PROM code into RAM and patching it
  (\ref{sec:build-reader}).
\item Read the volume directory (blocks 2--5) to [[DIR_BUF]].
\item Find the directory entry named \texttt{PRODOS} with file type
  \texttt{SYS}.
\item Load that file's data blocks at [[KERNEL_ENTRY]] and jump to it.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Layout and defines}

The boot block uses the same zero-page locations as the controller
PROM, plus a scratch area of its own. The PROM leaves the slot number
times 16 in [[ZP_SLOT16]] and the X~register, and maintains its
destination-page pointer at [[ZP_SECTOR_BUF]]; the boot code reuses
both, along with the PROM's sector ([[ZP_SECTOR]]) and track
([[ZP_CUR_TRACK]], [[ZP_TRG_TRACK]]) cells, so that the relocated PROM
code keeps working unmodified.

<<boot1 defines>>=
; --- Zero page: controller PROM workspace (reused by the boot code) ---
ZP_SECTOR_BUF   EQU $26         ; PROM read destination pointer (lo, hi)
ZP_SLOT16       EQU $2B         ; boot slot * 16, set by the PROM
ZP_FIELD_NIB    EQU $31         ; nibble scratch inside the PROM field reader
ZP_SECTOR       EQU $3D         ; physical sector to read
ZP_CUR_TRACK    EQU $40         ; track the head is on now
ZP_TRG_TRACK    EQU $41         ; track the PROM reader expects in address fields
; --- Zero page: ProDOS block-read interface ---
ZP_CMD          EQU $42         ; command for smart controllers: 1 = READ
ZP_UNIT         EQU $43         ; unit number (slot * 16)
ZP_IOBUF        EQU $44         ; data buffer pointer passed to the reader
ZP_BLOCK        EQU $46         ; block number to read
; --- Zero page: boot block scratch ---
ZP_READ_VEC     EQU $48         ; pointer: block-read entry (also ROM scan ptr)
ZP_DIR_PTR      EQU $4A         ; directory entry ptr / index-block lo-byte ptr
ZP_IDXHI_PTR    EQU $4C         ; index-block hi-byte ptr
ZP_BLK_IDX      EQU $4E         ; index of next data block within index block
ZP_PREV_HALF    EQU $50         ; previous half-track (phase to release)
ZP_TRG_HALF     EQU $51         ; target half-track (track * 2)
ZP_TIMEOUT      EQU $52         ; sector-search timeout, outer counter
ZP_CUR_HALF     EQU $53         ; current half-track (phase to energize)
ZP_SEEK_HI      EQU $54         ; cleared alongside the seek state
ZP_DATA_BUF     EQU $60         ; destination buffer for block reads
; --- Buffers and entry points outside this binary ---
DIR_BUF         EQU $0C00       ; volume directory read buffer (4 blocks)
INDEX_BUF       EQU $1E00       ; kernel file's index block buffer
KERNEL_ENTRY    EQU $2000       ; ProDOS kernel load address and entry
RELOC_TAIL      EQU $0A7F       ; where the reader tail is appended at runtime
; --- ROM entry points ---
MON_HOME        EQU $FC58       ; monitor: clear screen
MON_PRERR       EQU $FF2D       ; monitor: print "ERR" and sound bell
A3_ROM_EXIT     EQU $F479       ; Apple /// ROM: boot-failure exit
; --- Disk II controller soft switches (indexed by slot * 16) ---
IWM_PHASE0      EQU $C080       ; stepper phase 0 off; +1 on, +2/+3 phase 1...
IWM_MOTOR_OFF   EQU $C088       ; drive motor off
IWM_MOTOR_ON    EQU $C089       ; drive motor on
IWM_Q6L         EQU $C08C       ; read data latch
@ %def ZP_SECTOR_BUF ZP_SLOT16 ZP_FIELD_NIB ZP_SECTOR ZP_CUR_TRACK ZP_TRG_TRACK
@ %def ZP_CMD ZP_UNIT ZP_IOBUF ZP_BLOCK ZP_READ_VEC ZP_DIR_PTR ZP_IDXHI_PTR
@ %def ZP_BLK_IDX ZP_PREV_HALF ZP_TRG_HALF ZP_TIMEOUT ZP_CUR_HALF ZP_SEEK_HI
@ %def ZP_DATA_BUF DIR_BUF INDEX_BUF KERNEL_ENTRY RELOC_TAIL
@ %def MON_HOME MON_PRERR A3_ROM_EXIT
@ %def IWM_PHASE0 IWM_MOTOR_OFF IWM_MOTOR_ON IWM_Q6L

\section{Entry and controller detection}

Byte 0 of the boot sector is the sector count the PROM honors. It
starts as 1 --- the PROM loads just this sector --- and the code below
rewrites it to 3 before re-entering the PROM, which then fetches
physical sectors 1 and~2 to the following pages. (Sector~1 belongs to
a file's data and is simply overwritten later; sector~2 is the second
half of this block, landing at [[$0900]].)

<<boot1 sector count>>=
        ORG $0800
BOOT_BASE
        DC.B $01                        ; sectors for the PROM to load
@ %def BOOT_BASE

The same 512 bytes also boot an Apple~///, whose ROM loads block~0 at
\$A000 in its own address space and enters past the count byte with
carry clear, so the [[BCS]] falls through to the [[JMP]]. The operand
[[SOS_ABORT+$9800]] is the Apple~///-relative address of the abort
routine below ([[$0932]] seen at \$A132); an Apple~/// disk would carry
SOS boot code there instead, so on this ProDOS-only disk the ///~path
just reports a failed boot.

On the Apple~II the PROM enters at [[BOOT_ENTRY]] with carry state
undefined, so the [[SEC]] forces the branch. The routine then probes
the last byte of the controller card's ROM ([[$CnFF]]): zero marks a
Disk~II 16-sector controller, which can only deliver one sector at a
time and needs the full treatment; non-zero marks an intelligent
controller (hard disk, 3.5'' drive) that has already deposited the
whole 512-byte block and whose ROM provides a block-read entry point
at \$Cn00 plus that byte.

A on entry holds the PROM's sector count (the byte at [[BOOT_BASE]]):
1~the first time, 3~after the re-entered PROM has also loaded the
second half. The [[CMP]]/[[PHP]]/[[PLP]] dance preserves that
distinction across the slot computation, and the carry then selects
phase one (load the rest) or phase two ([[BUILD_READER]]).

<<boot1 entry>>=
        ORG $0801
BOOT_ENTRY
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Boot block entry from the controller ROM.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   X          - boot slot * 16 (from the PROM)
        ;   A          - PROM sector count: 1 on first entry, 3 on re-entry
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Distinguishes Apple II from Apple ///, then Disk II from
        ;   intelligent controllers ($CnFF == 0 means Disk II). First
        ;   Disk II entry: bump the sector count to 3 and re-enter the
        ;   PROM to load the rest of the boot block. Second entry:
        ;   continue at BUILD_READER. Intelligent controller: continue
        ;   at SET_READ_VECTOR with A = $CnFF entry offset.
        SEC                             ; Apple II: force the branch
        BCS .apple2
        JMP SOS_ABORT+$9800             ; Apple ///: block is at $A000
.apple2 STX ZP_UNIT
        CMP #$03                        ; carry <- second entry
        PHP
        TXA                             ; A <- slot * 16
        AND #$70
        LSR
        LSR
        LSR
        LSR
        ORA #$C0                        ; A <- $Cn, controller ROM page
        STA ZP_READ_VEC+1
        LDY #$FF
        STY ZP_READ_VEC                 ; ZP_READ_VEC -> $CnFF
        PLP
        INY                             ; Y <- 0
        LDA (ZP_READ_VEC),Y             ; last byte of controller ROM
        BNE SET_READ_VECTOR             ; nonzero: intelligent controller
        BCS BUILD_READER                ; Disk II, second entry
        ; --- Disk II, first entry: fetch the rest of the boot block ---
        LDA #$03
        STA BOOT_BASE                   ; sector count <- #$03
        INC ZP_SECTOR                   ; skip physical sector 1
        LDA ZP_READ_VEC+1               ; push $Cn5B as return address:
        PHA                             ;   re-enters the PROM read loop
        LDA #$5B                        ;   at $Cn5C with the new count
        PHA
        RTS
@ %def BOOT_ENTRY

The PROM's read loop advances its destination page and its sector
counter separately; incrementing [[ZP_SECTOR]] before re-entry makes
it read physical sector~2 (skipping~1) into the next page, [[$0900]]
--- which is exactly where ProDOS block~0's second half belongs, since
consecutive ProDOS sectors sit two physical sectors apart. When the
count reaches 3 the PROM jumps back to [[BOOT_ENTRY]] with
$A = 3$.

\section{Building a standalone sector reader}
\label{sec:build-reader}

The PROM can read sectors, but only as part of its boot sequence ---
it always starts over from track~0, sector~0, page [[$0800]]. To read
arbitrary blocks the boot code steals the PROM's sector-reading core:
it copies [[$Cn63]]--[[$CnEA]] (the address-field search, data-field
read, and denibbling loop) to [[RELOC_READER]]--[[$0A7E]], then makes
three kinds of surgical edits:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Seven single-byte patches} (offsets and values from
  [[PATCH_OFFSET]]/[[PATCH_BYTE]], applied relative to
  [[READ_NIBBLE]]). These retarget the routine's internal branches for
  its new home --- chiefly the error/retry paths, which now restart
  the boot block's own timeout-counting search loop instead of the
  PROM's.
\item \textbf{A seven-byte tail} ([[READER_TAIL]]) appended at
  [[RELOC_TAIL]]: \emph{LDX ZP\_SLOT16 / CLC / RTS} --- so a
  successful sector read returns to the caller with carry clear ---
  followed by \emph{JMP SEEK\_READ}, the patched-in retry used when
  the address field shows the head is on the wrong track.
\item \textbf{A fourteen-byte splice} ([[SPLICE_A]]/[[SPLICE_B]],
  copied over the start of the relocated code by [[APPLY_PATCH]]): a
  tighter prologue search that hunts for the \$D5~\$AA nibble pair
  marking the start of any sector field, branching back into the
  timeout loop on every miss.
\end{enumerate}

The copy source pointer is [[ZP_READ_VEC]], still aimed at the
controller ROM page; A is zero here (the [[$CnFF]] byte), zeroing both
the pointer's low byte and [[ZP_CUR_TRACK]] (the head is on track~0
after booting).

<<build the relocated sector reader>>=
        ORG $0831
BUILD_READER
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Construct a standalone sector reader at RELOC_READER from
        ; the controller PROM's own code.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A            - zero (the $CnFF byte that routed us here)
        ;   ZP_READ_VEC+1 - $Cn, controller ROM page
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Copy $Cn63-$CnEA to RELOC_READER..$0A7E, apply seven
        ;   relocation patches plus a 14-byte prologue-search splice
        ;   and a 7-byte exit tail, then fall into SET_READ_VECTOR
        ;   with ZP_READ_VEC aimed at DISKII_READ_BLOCK.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_CUR_TRACK, ZP_READ_VEC, RELOC_READER..RELOC_TAIL+6
        STA ZP_CUR_TRACK                ; ZP_CUR_TRACK <- #$00
        STA ZP_READ_VEC                 ; ZP_READ_VEC -> $Cn00
        LDY #$63
.copy   LDA (ZP_READ_VEC),Y             ; PROM code $Cn63..$CnEA
        STA RELOC_READER-$63,Y          ; -> RELOC_READER..$0A7E
        INY
        CPY #$EB
        BNE .copy
        LDX #$06
.patch  LDY PATCH_OFFSET,X
        LDA PATCH_BYTE,X
        STA READ_NIBBLE,Y               ; retarget branches in the copy
        LDA READER_TAIL,X
        JSR APPLY_PATCH                 ; append tail byte, redo splice
        DEX
        BPL .patch
        LDA #>DISKII_READ_BLOCK
        STA ZP_READ_VEC+1
        LDA #<DISKII_READ_BLOCK
        ; falls through to SET_READ_VECTOR
@ %def BUILD_READER

\section{Loading the volume directory}

Both controller flavors converge here with A holding the low byte of
the block-read entry: [[<DISKII_READ_BLOCK]] for a Disk~II, or the
[[$CnFF]] byte for an intelligent controller (whose entry is then
[[$Cn00]] plus that byte; values of [[$F9]] and up are reserved and
rejected). [[ZP_READ_VEC]] becomes the uniform ``read one block''
interface used by [[READ_BLOCK]]: block number in [[ZP_BLOCK]], buffer
in [[ZP_DATA_BUF]], command 1 (READ) in [[ZP_CMD]], unit in
[[ZP_UNIT]], carry set on return means failure.

The volume directory occupies blocks 2--5; all four are read to
[[DIR_BUF]]--[[$13FF]] before the search starts. A key block whose
previous-block link at [[DIR_BUF]] is non-zero is not really the start
of the directory, so the boot fails.

<<set read vector and load the volume directory>>=
        ORG $085B
SET_READ_VECTOR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Finalize the block-read vector, then read directory blocks
        ; 2..5 into DIR_BUF.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A  - low byte of the block-read entry point
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Reject entry bytes >= $F9, store the vector, zero the
        ;   block-read parameter area, then loop READ_BLOCK over
        ;   blocks 2..5 with the buffer advancing $200 per block.
        ;   Falls into FIND_KERNEL.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_READ_VEC, ZP_DATA_BUF, ZP_DIR_PTR, ZP_IDXHI_PTR,
        ;   ZP_BLK_IDX, ZP_CMD, ZP_BLOCK, DIR_BUF..$13FF
        LDY #$00
        CMP #$F9                        ; $F9..$FF: not a boot device
        BCS .fail_nz
        STA ZP_READ_VEC
        STY ZP_DATA_BUF
        STY ZP_DIR_PTR
        STY ZP_IDXHI_PTR
        STY ZP_BLK_IDX
        STY ZP_BLOCK+1
        INY
        STY ZP_CMD                      ; ZP_CMD <- #$01 = READ
        INY
        STY ZP_BLOCK                    ; ZP_BLOCK <- #$0002, directory key
        LDA #>DIR_BUF
        STA ZP_DATA_BUF+1
        STA ZP_DIR_PTR+1
.read   JSR READ_BLOCK
        BCS FAIL_C
        INC ZP_DATA_BUF+1               ; buffer += $200
        INC ZP_DATA_BUF+1
        INC ZP_BLOCK
        LDA ZP_BLOCK
        CMP #$06                        ; blocks 2..5
        BCC .read
        LDA DIR_BUF                     ; key block must have no
        ORA DIR_BUF+1                   ;   previous-block link
.fail_nz
        BNE BOOT_FAIL
        ; falls through to FIND_KERNEL
@ %def SET_READ_VECTOR

(The [[.fail_nz]] branch doubles as the bad-entry-byte rejection
above: an entry byte of [[$F9]] exactly would leave the zero flag set
and slip through --- a latent quirk in Apple's code, harmless in
practice.)

\section{Finding the kernel's directory entry}

Directory entries are [[$27]] bytes long (read from the entry-length
field of the volume header rather than assumed), 13 per block, first
entry at offset 4 past the block's 4-byte header. The scan walks
[[ZP_DIR_PTR]] through all four blocks of [[DIR_BUF]]; crossing onto
an even page means a new 512-byte block, so the entry offset resets to
4, and reaching page [[$14]] means the directory is exhausted ---
there is no \texttt{PRODOS} here, and the boot fails.

The name comparison covers the length byte itself ([[KERNEL_NAME]]
starts [[$26]]: storage type 2 in the high nibble, name length 6 in
the low), so only a \emph{sapling} file (2 levels, 512 bytes to 128K)
with the exact name \texttt{PRODOS} matches; the [[AND]]/[[CMP]]
re-check of the storage type after the loop is belt and braces. The
file must also have type [[$FF]] (\texttt{SYS}). Its key-block number
--- the index block --- comes from entry offset [[$11]].

<<find the kernel directory entry>>=
        ORG $0892
FIND_KERNEL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Scan the volume directory in DIR_BUF for a sapling SYS file
        ; named PRODOS.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Advance ZP_DIR_PTR entry by entry (length from the volume
        ;   header). Compare each entry's storage/length byte and name
        ;   against KERNEL_NAME. On match, validate type SYS and load
        ;   the key (index) block number into ZP_BLOCK. Exhausting the
        ;   directory fails the boot.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   ZP_BLOCK - index block of the kernel file
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_DIR_PTR, ZP_BLOCK
        LDA #$04                        ; first entry: offset 4 in block
        BNE .add                        ; always (A nonzero)
.next   LDA ZP_DIR_PTR
.add    CLC
        ADC DIR_BUF+$23                 ; + entry length from volume header
        TAY
        BCC .set
        INC ZP_DIR_PTR+1
        LDA ZP_DIR_PTR+1
        LSR                             ; odd page: same block, keep going
        BCS .set
        CMP #$0A                        ; page $14: past the directory
        BEQ BOOT_FAIL
        LDY #$04                        ; new block: entries restart at 4
.set    STY ZP_DIR_PTR
        LDA KERNEL_NAME
        AND #$0F                        ; Y <- name length (6)
        TAY
.cmp    LDA (ZP_DIR_PTR),Y              ; compare storage/len byte + name
        CMP KERNEL_NAME,Y
        BNE .next
        DEY
        BPL .cmp
        AND #$F0                        ; A = storage/len byte after loop
        CMP #$20                        ; must be a sapling file
        BNE BOOT_FAIL
        LDY #$10
        LDA (ZP_DIR_PTR),Y              ; file type
        CMP #$FF                        ; must be SYS
        BNE BOOT_FAIL
        INY
        LDA (ZP_DIR_PTR),Y              ; key block (index block) number
        STA ZP_BLOCK
        INY
        LDA (ZP_DIR_PTR),Y
        STA ZP_BLOCK+1
        ; falls through to LOAD_KERNEL
@ %def FIND_KERNEL

\section{Loading the kernel}

A sapling file's key block is an \emph{index block}: up to 256 data
block numbers, low bytes in the first half, high bytes in the second.
The loader reads the index block itself to [[INDEX_BUF]], aims
[[ZP_DIR_PTR]] (reused) at its low-byte half and [[ZP_IDXHI_PTR]] at
its high-byte half, then streams data blocks to [[KERNEL_ENTRY]]
onward, 512 bytes at a time, until the next block number is zero.
ProDOS~1.1.1 is 29 blocks; control then transfers to the kernel's
relocator at [[KERNEL_ENTRY]], and the boot block's job is done.

<<load the kernel>>=
        ORG $08D6
LOAD_KERNEL
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Read the kernel file's data blocks to KERNEL_ENTRY and run it.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_BLOCK - index block number of the kernel file
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Read the index block to INDEX_BUF; then repeatedly fetch
        ;   the next data block number from it (lo half / hi half)
        ;   and read that block, advancing the buffer $200 each time,
        ;   until a block number of 0 terminates the file.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_DIR_PTR, ZP_IDXHI_PTR, ZP_DATA_BUF, ZP_BLOCK,
        ;   ZP_BLK_IDX, INDEX_BUF, KERNEL_ENTRY..
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_DIR_PTR
        LDY #>INDEX_BUF
        STY ZP_DIR_PTR+1                ; -> index block, low bytes
        STY ZP_DATA_BUF+1               ; first read target: INDEX_BUF
        INY
        STY ZP_IDXHI_PTR+1              ; -> index block, high bytes
.read   JSR READ_BLOCK
FAIL_C  BCS BOOT_FAIL
        INC ZP_DATA_BUF+1               ; buffer += $200
        INC ZP_DATA_BUF+1               ;   (INDEX_BUF -> KERNEL_ENTRY ...)
        LDY ZP_BLK_IDX
        INC ZP_BLK_IDX
        LDA (ZP_DIR_PTR),Y              ; next data block number
        STA ZP_BLOCK
        LDA (ZP_IDXHI_PTR),Y
        STA ZP_BLOCK+1
        ORA (ZP_DIR_PTR),Y              ; block 0 terminates the file
        BNE .read
        JMP KERNEL_ENTRY
@ %def LOAD_KERNEL FAIL_C

([[FAIL_C]] is the error branch for every [[READ_BLOCK]] call in the
boot --- the directory loop's failure case branches here too, because
[[BOOT_FAIL]] is out of its branch range.)

\section{Failure trampoline and the kernel's name}

Every failure path funnels through [[BOOT_FAIL]]. Its [[JMP]]
instruction straddles the sector boundary: the opcode is the last byte
of the first sector and the operand is the first two bytes of the
second --- so a boot failure on a disk whose second sector never
loaded would jump through whatever bytes happen to be at [[$0900]].

<<boot failure and kernel file name>>=
        ORG $08FF
BOOT_FAIL
        ; trampoline: every error path funnels here
        JMP DISK_ERROR
KERNEL_NAME
        DC.B $26                        ; storage type 2 | name length 6
        DC.B "PRODOS         "          ; 15-character name field
@ %def BOOT_FAIL KERNEL_NAME

\section{The block-read dispatcher}

All block reads go through this thunk: it copies the caller-visible
buffer pointer [[ZP_DATA_BUF]] into [[ZP_IOBUF]] (the location
intelligent-controller firmware expects) and jumps through
[[ZP_READ_VEC]] --- to [[DISKII_READ_BLOCK]] or to controller
firmware, whichever [[SET_READ_VECTOR]] installed.

<<smart controller dispatch>>=
        ORG $0912
READ_BLOCK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Read one 512-byte block: number in ZP_BLOCK, buffer in
        ; ZP_DATA_BUF.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Copy ZP_DATA_BUF to ZP_IOBUF and dispatch through
        ;   ZP_READ_VEC.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   carry set on failure
        LDA ZP_DATA_BUF
        STA ZP_IOBUF
        LDA ZP_DATA_BUF+1
        STA ZP_IOBUF+1
        JMP (ZP_READ_VEC)
@ %def READ_BLOCK

\section{Reader patch tables}

The data behind section~\ref{sec:build-reader}: patch offsets are
relative to [[READ_NIBBLE]], and the tail is raw machine code deposited
at [[RELOC_TAIL]] (disassembled in the comments).

<<reader patch tables>>=
        ORG $091D
PATCH_OFFSET                            ; patch locations - READ_NIBBLE
        HEX 08 1e 24 3f 45 47 76
PATCH_BYTE                              ; values written there
        HEX d0 d7 d1 b6 4b b4 ac
READER_TAIL                             ; appended at RELOC_TAIL:
        DC.B $A6,$2B                    ;   LDX ZP_SLOT16
        DC.B $18                        ;   CLC (sector read OK)
        DC.B $60                        ;   RTS
        DC.B $4C                        ;   JMP SEEK_READ (wrong-track retry)
        DC.W SEEK_READ
@ %def PATCH_OFFSET PATCH_BYTE READER_TAIL

\section{Error handlers}

The Apple~/// path: push [[$9FFF]] as a return address and call the
///~ROM's boot-exit routine with $A=1$ (boot error), $X=0$.

<<apple iii abort>>=
        ORG $0932
SOS_ABORT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Apple /// boot failure: re-enter the /// ROM.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Push $9FFF as the return address and call the /// ROM
        ;   exit with A = 1 (boot error), X = 0. Never returns.
        LDA #$9F
        PHA
        LDA #$FF
        PHA
        LDA #$01
        LDX #$00
        JMP A3_ROM_EXIT
@ %def SOS_ABORT

The Apple~II path: clear the screen, print \texttt{ERR} with a bell,
and hang.

<<disk error handler>>=
        ORG $093F
DISK_ERROR
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Fatal boot error: clear screen, print "ERR", hang.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   MON_HOME, MON_PRERR, then spin forever.
        JSR MON_HOME
        JSR MON_PRERR
.hang   JMP .hang
@ %def DISK_ERROR

\section{Patch helper and splice bytes}

Called once per patch-table iteration with X descending 6 to 0; each
call appends one tail byte and (redundantly, all seven times) re-lays
the 14-byte prologue-search splice over the start of the relocated
reader. It also seeds [[ZP_FIELD_NIB]] with [[$AA]], a workspace byte
of the PROM's field reader.

<<apply one reader patch>>=
        ORG $0948
APPLY_PATCH
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Apply one byte of the reader tail plus the full splice.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A  - tail byte (from READER_TAIL)
        ;   X  - byte index, 6 down to 0
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Store the tail byte at RELOC_TAIL+X, copy SPLICE_A/_B over
        ;   RELOC_READER..RELOC_READER+13, seed ZP_FIELD_NIB with #$AA.
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   RELOC_TAIL+X, RELOC_READER..+13, ZP_FIELD_NIB
        STA RELOC_TAIL,X
        LDA SPLICE_A,X
        STA RELOC_READER,X
        LDA SPLICE_B,X
        STA RELOC_READER+7,X
        LDA #$AA
        STA ZP_FIELD_NIB
        RTS
@ %def APPLY_PATCH

The splice itself, as it executes at [[RELOC_READER]] (see
section~\ref{sec:seek-read} for the loop it cooperates with):

\begin{verbatim}
RELOC_READER  LSR                ; nibble was $D5? ($D5 >> 1 = $6A)
              CMP #$6A
              BNE near READ_NIBBLE    ; no: keep searching
              LDA IWM_Q6L,X      ; next nibble
              BPL *-3
              CMP #$AA           ; $D5 $AA = field prologue
              BNE near READ_NIBBLE    ; no: search on (timeout ticking)
              ...                ; falls into relocated PROM reader
\end{verbatim}

<<prolog search splice bytes>>=
        ORG $095C
SPLICE_A                                ; first 7 bytes of the splice
        HEX 4a c9 6a d0 f3 bd 8c
SPLICE_B                                ; second 7 bytes
        HEX c0 10 fb c9 aa d0 ea
        HEX aa aa aa                    ; unused filler
@ %def SPLICE_A SPLICE_B

\section{Stepper phase control}

One half-track step: energize or release (carry set/clear) the stepper
phase for a given half-track, then wait roughly 20\,ms for the head to
move. Phase number is half-track mod~4; the [[ROL]] folds the carry
into the soft-switch address's low bit (odd offsets energize). The
final [[LDX]] reloads the slot index --- and, since the slot byte is
never zero, guarantees the zero flag is clear on return, which
[[SEEK_READ]] uses to make its loop branch unconditional.

<<stepper phase control>>=
        ORG $096D
STEP_PHASE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Pulse one stepper phase and wait for the head to settle.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   carry        - 1 = energize phase, 0 = release it
        ;   ZP_CUR_HALF  - half-track selecting the phase (entry 1)
        ;   A            - half-track (alternate entry STEP_PHASE_A)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Touch IWM_PHASE0 + (halftrack mod 4)*2 + carry, then
        ;   delay ~20 ms via a $2C x $11 countdown.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   Z = 0 always (X reloaded with the nonzero slot byte)
        ; Clobbers: A, X
        LDA ZP_CUR_HALF
STEP_PHASE_A
        AND #$03
        ROL                             ; A <- phase*2 + carry
        ORA ZP_SLOT16
        TAX
        LDA IWM_PHASE0,X                ; touch the phase switch
        LDA #$2C
        LDX #$11
.inner  DEX
        BNE .inner
        SBC #$01
        BNE .inner-2                    ; reload X, loop $2C times
        LDX ZP_SLOT16
        RTS
@ %def STEP_PHASE STEP_PHASE_A

\section{Reading a block on the Disk II}
\label{sec:diskii-read-block}

The Disk~II block-read entry installed in [[ZP_READ_VEC]]. It converts
the ProDOS block number to physical geometry --- track = block/8, and
first sector $= 4(b \bmod 4) + \lfloor (b \bmod 8)/4 \rfloor$, the
arithmetic form of the ProDOS interleave --- then reads the block's
two sectors. The two halves of a ProDOS block always lie exactly two
physical sectors apart, so the second read just increments
[[ZP_SECTOR]] twice. The PROM reader deposits whole 256-byte pages, so
the buffer page in [[ZP_SECTOR_BUF+1]] advances by one between reads.

<<disk ii block read>>=
        ORG $0986
DISKII_READ_BLOCK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Read ProDOS block ZP_BLOCK to the page pair at ZP_IOBUF.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_BLOCK   - block number (0..279)
        ;   ZP_IOBUF   - page-aligned destination buffer
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   sector <- 4*(block mod 4) + (block mod 8)/4, track <-
        ;   block/8; motor on; seek and read each of the block's two
        ;   sectors (two physical sectors apart); motor off.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   carry set on failure
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_SECTOR, ZP_TRG_TRACK, ZP_TRG_HALF, ZP_SECTOR_BUF+1
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA ZP_BLOCK
        AND #$07
        CMP #$04                        ; carry <- bit 2
        AND #$03
        PHP
        ASL
        PLP
        ROL                             ; A <- 4*(blk mod 4) + carry
        STA ZP_SECTOR
        LDA ZP_BLOCK+1
        LSR
        LDA ZP_BLOCK
        ROR
        LSR
        LSR
        STA ZP_TRG_TRACK                ; track <- block / 8
        ASL
        STA ZP_TRG_HALF
        LDA ZP_IOBUF+1
        STA ZP_SECTOR_BUF+1             ; PROM reader's destination page
        LDX ZP_SLOT16
        LDA IWM_MOTOR_ON,X
        JSR SEEK_READ                   ; first sector of the block
        INC ZP_SECTOR_BUF+1
        INC ZP_SECTOR                   ; second half: two sectors on
        INC ZP_SECTOR
        BCS .done                       ; first read timed out: give up
        JSR SEEK_READ                   ; second sector of the block
.done   LDY IWM_MOTOR_OFF,X
RD_EXIT RTS
@ %def DISKII_READ_BLOCK RD_EXIT

\section{Seek, settle, and the sector search}
\label{sec:seek-read}

[[SEEK_READ]] does everything between ``motor on'' and ``sector in
memory.'' First the seek: half-tracks are stepped one at a time from
[[ZP_CUR_TRACK]]$\times 2$ toward [[ZP_TRG_HALF]], energizing the new
phase and releasing the previous one each step. The closing [[BNE]] is
unconditional ([[STEP_PHASE]] guarantees $Z=0$), re-evaluating the
distance every iteration.

Then the search-with-timeout loop, the cleverest corner of the boot
block. [[ZP_TIMEOUT]] counts [[$7F]] passes of a [[$7F]]-iteration
inner loop (Y); each pass pushes saved flags with carry \emph{clear}
and falls into [[READ_NIBBLE]], where the spliced prologue search
(section~\ref{sec:build-reader}) reads nibbles hunting for \$D5~\$AA.
Misses branch back into the loop body, burning Y; when Y expires the
flags are popped and the outer counter decrements. If it reaches zero
the routine returns through [[RD_EXIT]] with carry \emph{set} ---
that [[SEC]] before the decrement is the error flag --- and the
failure propagates out of [[DISKII_READ_BLOCK]] to [[FAIL_C]]. On a
prologue hit, execution continues into the relocated PROM reader,
which checks that the address field matches [[ZP_TRG_TRACK]] and
[[ZP_SECTOR]] (a wrong track re-enters [[SEEK_READ]] via the patched
tail, after the PROM code updates [[ZP_CUR_TRACK]] from the address
field), denibbles the data field into page [[ZP_SECTOR_BUF+1]], and
returns carry-clear through the appended tail at [[RELOC_TAIL]].

<<seek and read sector>>=
        ORG $09BC
SEEK_READ
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Seek to ZP_TRG_HALF and read physical sector ZP_SECTOR into
        ; page ZP_SECTOR_BUF+1, via the relocated PROM reader.
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   ZP_CUR_TRACK   - track the head is on
        ;   ZP_TRG_HALF    - destination half-track
        ;   ZP_SECTOR      - physical sector wanted
        ;   ZP_SECTOR_BUF+1 - destination page
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Step the head one half-track at a time to the target,
        ;   then search for a field prologue with a $7F x $7F nibble
        ;   timeout, falling into the relocated PROM reader on a hit.
        ;
        ; Outputs:
        ;   carry clear = sector read; carry set = timeout
        ;
        ; Modifies:
        ;   ZP_CUR_HALF, ZP_PREV_HALF, ZP_SEEK_HI, ZP_TIMEOUT
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        LDA ZP_CUR_TRACK
        ASL
        STA ZP_CUR_HALF
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_SEEK_HI
        ; --- step toward the target one half-track at a time ---
.step   LDA ZP_CUR_HALF
        STA ZP_PREV_HALF
        SEC
        SBC ZP_TRG_HALF
        BEQ .settle                     ; arrived
        BCS .dec
        INC ZP_CUR_HALF                 ; target is further in
        BCC .move
.dec    DEC ZP_CUR_HALF                 ; target is further out
.move   SEC
        JSR STEP_PHASE                  ; energize new half-track phase
        LDA ZP_PREV_HALF
        CLC
        JSR STEP_PHASE_A                ; release previous phase
        BNE .step                       ; always (Z=0 from STEP_PHASE)
        ; --- prologue search with timeout ---
.settle LDY #$7F
        STY ZP_TIMEOUT
        PHP                             ; keep a flags byte on the stack
.tick   PLP
        SEC                             ; carry set = timeout error
        DEC ZP_TIMEOUT
        BEQ RD_EXIT                     ; give up (returns carry set)
        CLC
        PHP                             ; saved carry clear for the reader
        DEY
        BEQ .tick
READ_NIBBLE
        LDA IWM_Q6L,X                   ; next nibble from the drive
        BPL READ_NIBBLE
        ; falls into the spliced prologue search at RELOC_READER
@ %def SEEK_READ READ_NIBBLE

\section{The relocated reader area}

On disk the rest of the block is zero. At runtime
[[BUILD_READER]] fills [[RELOC_READER]] (and onward past the end of
this block, to [[RELOC_TAIL]]+6) with the patched copy of the
controller PROM's sector reader.

<<relocated reader area>>=
        ORG $09F7
RELOC_READER
        HEX 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
        HEX 00                          ; filled at boot time
@ %def RELOC_READER

