\chapter{The resident library: STUPH}

\texttt{STUPH} is not ``graphics/shape data'' --- it is the game's
\textbf{resident low-memory library}: 6144 bytes loaded at
[[$0800]]--[[$1FFF]] and never unloaded. Everything machine-specific
lives here: the glyph banks and the font blitter, the hi-res address
tables, double-buffered page flipping, the tile-map renderer, the
keyboard type-ahead queue, sound effects and their queue, a lagged
additive random-number generator, line drawing for the dungeon view,
and the machine-detection code that turns an AppleMouse card into a
vertical-blank interrupt source and tames a IIgs down to 1\,MHz when
timing matters. The engine (\texttt{MI.U1}) and every overlay reach
all of it through a \textbf{jump-vector table at [[$1583]]}, three
bytes per entry, so the library's internals can move without
re-assembling its callers. \texttt{MI.U1}'s overlay dispatcher
\textsc{bload}s \texttt{STUPH} by name, which is how it gets here.

For a porter, this chapter is the platform layer: every routine in it
corresponds to a primitive you must supply on a new platform ---
blit-glyph, draw-map-row, get-key, play-effect, random ---
and everything above it in \texttt{MI.U1} and the overlays is
platform-independent game logic calling these vectors.

\textbf{The memory map of the module:}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{llp{7.5cm}}
[[$0800]]--[[$0BFF]] & [[FONT_BANK]] & 128 glyphs $\times$ 8 scanlines
  (text font; chars [[$00]]--[[$19]] are terrain-strip pairs) \\
[[$0C00]]--[[$11FF]] & [[TILE_BANK]] & 96 glyphs $\times$ 16 scanlines
  (the map tile set: 48 two-glyph tiles) \\
[[$1200]]--[[$137F]] & [[HGR_ROW_LO]]/[[HGR_ROW_HI]] & hi-res address
  of each of the 192 screen scanlines \\
[[$1380]]--[[$157F]] & [[XCOL_TBL]]/[[XMASK_TBL]] & pixel
  column $\to$ screen byte / bit mask, for [[PLOT]] \\
[[$1580]]--[[$15E8]] & flags + vectors & three flag bytes, then 34
  three-byte [[JMP]] vectors \\
[[$15E9]]--[[$1E39]] & code & the routines themselves \\
[[$1E3A]]--[[$1FFF]] & --- & zero fill \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Double buffering.} The library draws hi-res graphics on one
page while displaying the other. Zero page [[ZP_PAGE_XOR]] holds the
value XORed into every screen-address high byte before writing:
[[$00]] draws on page 1 ([[$2000]]), [[$60]] on page 2 ([[$4000]]).
[[ZP_PAGE_TGL]] holds the XOR distance to the \emph{other} page ---
[[$60]] when double-buffering, [[$00]] to pin everything on one page.
[[PAGE_FLIP]] displays the page just drawn and toggles
[[ZP_PAGE_XOR]]. The text routines ([[FONT_DRAW]], the scrolls and
clears) deliberately write \emph{both} pages, so the text windows
survive page flips without redrawing; only the map viewport and
pixel graphics are truly double-buffered.

\textbf{Inverse video.} [[ZP_INVERSE]] is EORed into every byte the
text routines emit: [[$00]] for white-on-black, [[$7F]] for inverse.
The engine flips it to flash low hit points and food.

