\section{The glyph banks}

Two banks of 1-byte-wide glyph bitmaps open the module. Both are
stored \emph{plane-major}: all glyphs' scanline 0, then all glyphs'
scanline 1, and so on --- so drawing one glyph reads one byte per
plane at a fixed index, and animating a glyph can rotate bytes
through the planes with a constant stride.

\textbf{Bank A, the font} ([[FONT_BANK]]): 128 glyphs of 8 scanlines;
scanline $s$ of glyph $g$ is at [[FONT_BANK]]$ + 128s + g$. Glyphs
[[$20]]--[[$7F]] are the ASCII text font (with true lowercase ---
1986!), drawn identically in any column. Glyphs [[$00]]--[[$19]] are
\emph{terrain strips} used by the screen border, and they come in
pre-shifted pairs: [[FONT_DRAW]] adds one to the glyph index when
drawing them in an odd column, so their color pixels stay aligned.
Glyphs [[$7C]]--[[$7F]] are the four frames of the flashing cursor
([[CURSOR_FLASH]] cycles through them).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/stuph_font.png}
\caption{Bank A: the text font, 128 glyphs in index order
(row-major, 16 per row). Note the terrain strips in the first two
rows, the full lowercase set, and the cursor frames at the end.}
\label{fig:stuph-font}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Bank B, the map tiles} ([[TILE_BANK]]): 96 glyphs of 16
scanlines; scanline $s$ of glyph $g$ is at [[TILE_BANK]]$ + 96s + g$.
The map renderer pairs them: map cell code $c$ draws glyphs $c$
(left) and $c{+}1$ (right), so the effective tile set is 48 tiles of
$14 \times 16$ pixels. Water, plains, forest, mountains; castles,
towers, cities and dungeon entrances; the player on foot, horse,
cart, raft and frigate; and the overworld monsters --- all visible
in the rendered sheet.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/stuph_tiles.png}
\caption{Bank B: the 48 outdoor map tiles (each two glyphs wide),
in code order. The first tile (top left) is open water, whose glyph
bytes [[DRAW_MAP]] rotates vertically to make it flow.}
\label{fig:stuph-tiles}
\end{figure}

The \texttt{MAPCHARS} file (\autoref{sec:mapchars}) is an
\emph{alternate bank A} that the town and castle overlays load over
[[FONT_BANK]]: its terrain strips become walls and counters, and it
adds an inverse-video capital alphabet for lettering shop signs
directly onto the map.

