\section{The disk prompt}

When a file operation fails with an error, the engine asks for the
right disk and retries. Two entry points pick the disk name ---
[[DISK_PROMPT]] (the \emph{Ultima} disk, with the classic
[[DC.B $2C]] skip over the second entry's [[LDX]]) and
[[DISK_PROMPT_P]] (the \emph{Player} disk). The carry is the
caller's error flag: called with carry clear nothing happens, so
callers can unconditionally [[JSR]] here after a load and loop on
the returned carry.

<<miu1 disk prompt>>=
        ORG $7DCC
DISK_PROMPT
        SUBROUTINE
        ; On error (C set), ask for the Ultima disk and return
        ; C set; on C clear, return immediately.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   X selects the disk name (0 = Ultima, 1 = Player);
        ;   print "Put in the <name> Disk", PRESS_SPACE, clear
        ;   the line, return C set so the caller retries.
        LDX #$00                        ; the Ultima disk
        DC.B $2C                        ; BIT abs: skip the LDX
DISK_PROMPT_P
        LDX #$01                        ; the Player disk
        BCC .rts                        ; no error: nothing to do
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B "}Put in the ",$00
        JSR STR_NTH
        DC.W DISK_NAMES
        JSR MSG_PRINT
        DC.B " Disk",$00
        JSR PRESS_SPACE
        JSR CLR_EOL
        SEC                             ; tell the caller to retry
.rts    RTS
DISK_NAMES
        DC.B "Ultim",$E1                ; "Ultima"
        DC.B "Playe",$F2                ; "Player"
@ %def DISK_PROMPT DISK_PROMPT_P DISK_NAMES

\section{Locking onto page 1}

Popups and overlay switches end double-buffering first:
[[PAGE1_LOCK]] makes page 1 the live image (copying the displayed
page onto it if page 1 was the stale buffer) and zeroes both page
variables, so every later draw lands directly on the visible
screen.

<<miu1 page1 lock>>=
        ORG $7E05
PAGE1_LOCK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; End double-buffering with the current image on page 1.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   If page 1 is the (stale) draw page, PAGE_COPY the
        ;   displayed image onto it. Show page 1; ZP_PAGE_XOR and
        ;   ZP_PAGE_TGL := 0 (all drawing now on the live page).
        LDA ZP_PAGE_XOR
        BNE .show                       ; page 2 was being drawn:
        JSR PAGE_COPY                   ;   page 1 already shows
.show   BIT TXTPAGE1
        LDA #$00
        STA ZP_PAGE_XOR
        STA ZP_PAGE_TGL
        RTS
@ %def PAGE1_LOCK

\section{The player state block}

Everything the game knows about the player lives in one block at
[[LOC_NAME]]--[[$7EF1]], and the engine ships with a snapshot of a
mid-game character already in it --- \emph{Glinda}, female, 900 hit
points, 2104 coin --- presumably whatever save was loaded when this
disk image was mastered. \texttt{GEN} rewrites the block for a new
game, and the save and restore commands move it to and from
\texttt{/U1.PLAYER} (whose pathname sits right here in the block).

The block opens with the location-name table that [[GAME_LOAD]]
indexes (the current location's name at offset 0, the seven overlay
names at fixed 4-byte offsets), and ends with a stretch of zeroed
working storage reaching to the text-reader code at [[MSG_GETC]].
A few fields' meanings are not yet pinned down; they are kept as
commented hex until an overlay shows how they are used.

