\section{TWN}

\texttt{TWN} --- the town overlay, 8461 bytes at [[$8956]]. It is the
mode the player drops into on entering any of the game's towns (and
shares its loader and most of its machinery with \texttt{CAS}, the
castle overlay of the next section). Where \texttt{OUT} is the
top-down overworld and \texttt{DNG} the first-person dungeon, a town
is a single \emph{walled map} drawn in the same tile font as the
overworld but populated by named people: shopkeepers behind their
counters, guards on patrol, and wandering townsfolk. The town
overlay's job is to draw that map, animate its inhabitants, and route
the player's commands --- most of which, in town, mean
\emph{talking}: buying, selling, dropping coins, stealing.

The map data itself lives in \texttt{TCMAPS} (decoded in the data
appendix): a directory of ten 764-byte records, each a
$38\times18$ grid of [[MAPCHARS]] glyph codes followed by an
80-byte table of non-player characters. On entry \texttt{TWN}
[[BLOAD]]s \texttt{TCMAPS} and \texttt{MAPCHARS}, copies the one
record for this place into a live buffer at [[TOWN_MAP]], and draws
it.

\subsection{The live map buffer}

The chosen \texttt{TCMAPS} record is copied to [[TOWN_MAP]], a
768-byte buffer just above the overlay. Its first
$38\times18 = 684$ bytes are the displayed cells; the remaining bytes
hold five parallel 16-entry arrays describing the up to sixteen NPCs:
[[NPC_TYPE]], [[NPC_X]], [[NPC_Y]], and a 16-bit hit-point value in
[[NPC_HP]]. A type byte of [[$FF]] marks an empty slot; the low values
are the people --- a shopkeeper, a guard, a wanderer --- each drawn at
its $(x,y)$ through the sprite-glyph table [[NPC_GLYPH]]. The eighteen
[[MAP_ROW_LO]]/[[MAP_ROW_HI]] pointers give the start of each map row
within the buffer (stride 38).

\subsection{Engine and state symbols}

\texttt{TWN} reuses the resident-library and \texttt{MI.U1} engine API
exactly as the other overlays do, plus the shared player-state block.
Only the town-specific zero-page scratch, the \texttt{TWN} BSS state
variables, and the in-file tables are new.

