The generator's own helpers sit just past the renderer. Note
what [[EDGE_PICK]] does to its table: [[EDGE_FEATURE]] holds
codes 2 and 9 (trapdoors), but they are intercepted and replaced
by 3 --- the lattice edges get secret doors where an earlier
design evidently put trapdoors.

<<dng generator helpers>>=
        ORG $A3F3
SEED_RND
        ; Step the deterministic maze generator: a Fibonacci-
        ; style swap-add on (SEED_A, SEED_B). A := new SEED_A.
        CLC
        LDA SEED_A
        ADC #$09
        ADC SEED_B
        LDX SEED_A
        STA SEED_A
        STX SEED_B
        RTS
EDGE_PICK
        SUBROUTINE
        ; A := a random lattice-edge feature.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   A seeded d20 over EDGE_FEATURE: open (0), secret
        ;   door (3) or door (4), weighted 6/6/8.
        JSR SEED_RND
        AND #$1F
        CMP #$14                        ; a d20 from the d32
        BCS EDGE_PICK
        TAX
        LDA EDGE_FEATURE,X
        CMP #$09                        ; the trapdoor entries
        BEQ .door                       ;   are overridden to
        CMP #$02                        ;   secret doors
        BEQ .door
        RTS
.door   LDA #$03
        RTS
CELL_WRITE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Store A into the map cell at column X, row Y.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   DNG_MAP[X + 11*Y] := A; X and A are preserved.
        PHA
        TXA
        CPY #$00
.row    BEQ .put
        CLC
        ADC #$0B
        DEY
        JMP .row
.put    TAY
        PLA
        STA DNG_MAP,Y
        RTS
NEGATE  ; A := -A
        EOR #$FF
        CLC
        ADC #$01
        RTS
AHEAD_XY
        ; X/Y := the cell one step in the facing direction
        LDA DNG_X
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DX
        TAX
        LDA DNG_Y
        CLC
        ADC DNG_DY
        TAY
        RTS
@ %def SEED_RND EDGE_PICK CELL_WRITE NEGATE AHEAD_XY

\section{DNG: the shape engine}

[[SHAPE_DRAW]] is a small scaled vector-stroke interpreter. It
draws the monsters, the chest and the ladder-cell glyph as
line figures that shrink with distance --- the same telescoping
the corridor uses, but applied to a free-form outline rather
than a box.

A shape is a list of signed $(\Delta x, \Delta y)$ steps. The
engine keeps a pen at [[WORK_X]]/[[WORK_Y]] and, for each step,
scales the delta down by [[SHAPE_SCALE]] halvings (so a shape at
depth $4$ is an eighth the size it is at depth $1$) and draws a
line to the new pen position --- unless the step's flag byte says
``move'', in which case it lifts the pen and just repositions. A
$(0,0)$ step ends the shape.

The shape \emph{pointers} live at the head of [[MON_SHAPES]] as a
table of words; [[SHAPE_DRAW]] indexes it by shape number, biases
the pointer (the stroke data is stored relative), and writes it
into its own fetch instruction --- classic self-modifying code,
which is why the disk image carries a stale [[$FFFF]] operand at
[[SHAPE_FETCH]]. A few shape indexes ([[$12]], [[$16]], [[$1C]])
get their starting Y nudged to a feature-specific baseline so the
chest sits on the floor and the tall monsters touch the ceiling.

<<dng shape draw>>=
        ORG $A449
SHAPE_DRAW
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Draw vector shape A at scale X (the view depth).
        ;
        ; Inputs:
        ;   A  -- shape index into MON_SHAPES
        ;   X  -- number of halvings (0 = full size, nearest)
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   Self-modify SHAPE_FETCH to point at the shape's stroke
        ;   list, set the pen baseline, then walk (dx,dy) steps:
        ;   scale each by SHAPE_SCALE and draw (or move) to the new
        ;   pen position until a (0,0) terminator.
        ; Clobbers: A, X, Y
        STX SHAPE_SCALE
        ASL                             ; word index into the pointer
        TAY                             ;   table
        LDA MON_SHAPES,Y
        CLC
        ADC #$92                        ; bias the stored pointer and
        STA SHAPE_PTR                   ;   patch SHAPE_FETCH's operand
        LDA MON_SHAPES+1,Y
        ADC #$A6
        STA SHAPE_PTR+1
        LDX VIEW_DEPTH
        DEX
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$90,X              ; default pen-Y baseline
        CPY #$12                        ; chest: sit on the floor
        BNE .chk16
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$22,X
.chk16  CPY #$16
        BNE .chk1C
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$54,X
.chk1C  CPY #$1C
        BNE .pen
        LDA DNG_GEOM+$5E,X
.pen    STA .penY                       ; store into the move below
.step   JSR SHAPE_FETCH                 ; dx
        STA ACC
        JSR SHAPE_SCALE_BYTE
        CLC
        ADC #$80                        ; pen-X origin = screen centre
        STA $08
        JSR SHAPE_FETCH                 ; dy
        TAX
        ORA ACC                         ; (0,0) terminates
        BNE .draw
        RTS
.draw   TXA
        JSR SHAPE_SCALE_BYTE
        CLC
.penY = *+1
        ADC #$5F                        ; pen-Y origin (patched above)
        STA $09
        LDA WORK_X
        STA $06
        LDA WORK_Y
        STA $07
        JSR SHAPE_FETCH                 ; flag: 0 = move (lift pen)
        CMP #$00
        BNE .line
        LDA $08
        STA $06
        LDA $09
        STA $07
.line   LDA $08                         ; advance the pen
        STA WORK_X
        LDA $09
        STA WORK_Y
        JSR LINE_AGAIN
        JMP .step
SHAPE_FETCH
        ; Read one shape byte and advance the self-modified pointer.
SHAPE_PTR = *+1
        LDA STALE_FFFF                  ; operand patched per shape
        INC SHAPE_PTR
        BNE .nohi
        INC SHAPE_PTR+1
.nohi   RTS
SHAPE_SCALE_BYTE
        SUBROUTINE
        ; Scale one signed shape coordinate down by the view depth.
        ;
        ; Behavior:
        ;   A := A arithmetic-shifted right SHAPE_SCALE times (sign
        ;   preserving via the captured carry), so coordinate deltas
        ;   shrink geometrically with depth.
        CLC
        CMP #$80                        ; capture the sign into carry
        BCC .pos
        SEC
.pos    PHP
        LDX SHAPE_SCALE
        BEQ .done
.halve  PLP
        PHP
        ROR                             ; carry = sign keeps it signed
        DEX
        BNE .halve
.done   PLP
        RTS
@ %def SHAPE_DRAW SHAPE_FETCH SHAPE_PTR SHAPE_SCALE_BYTE

\section{DNG: state}

The overlay's variables live inside the file image (all zero on
disk) rather than in BSS proper --- only the map itself sits past
the end. [[ACC]]/[[ACC_HI]] and friends are general scratch;
they appear under one name each even where a routine borrows
them for something else (the comments at each use tell the local
story).

<<dng state>>=
        ORG $A4E8
DNG_X   DC.B $00                        ; player column, 0-10
DNG_Y   DC.B $00                        ; player row, 0-10
TGT_X   DC.B $00                        ; target/probe cell
TGT_Y   DC.B $00
DNG_DX  DC.B $00                        ; facing vector: one of
DNG_DY  DC.B $00                        ;   (0,+/-1), (+/-1,0)
WORK_X  DC.B $00                        ; scratch coordinates
WORK_Y  DC.B $00                        ;   (generator, Blink)
ADDEND  DC.B $00                        ; MUL_ADD addend; damage
ADDEND_HI
        DC.B $00                        ;   sample (16-bit)
ACC     DC.B $00                        ; 16-bit accumulator /
ACC_HI  DC.B $00                        ;   general scratch
TMP_CNT DC.B $00                        ; treasure item count;
                                        ;   attack damage high
SHAPE_SCALE
        DC.B $00                        ; SHAPE_DRAW: halvings
SLOT_SAVE
        DC.B $00                        ; MON_DIST's saved slot
VIEW_DEPTH
        DC.B $00                        ; cells ahead being drawn
DIST    DC.B $00                        ; dx^2+dy^2, then the
        DC.B $00                        ;   root / remainder
SQRT_STEP
        DC.B $00                        ; odd-number subtractor
        DC.B $00                        ;   (also dy^2)
FIGHT_FLAG
        DC.B $00                        ; combat printed: reprompt
        DC.B $00                        ; (unused)
MON_SLOT
        DC.B $00                        ; slot being processed,
                                        ;   1-5; also the view's
                                        ;   monster nibble
RANGE_CNT
        DC.B $00                        ; attack reach countdown
STEP_X  DC.B $00                        ; monster approach step,
STEP_Y  DC.B $00                        ;   -1/0/+1 per axis
        DC.B $00                        ; (unused)
NEG_TMP DC.B $00                        ; MON_DIST negate scratch
SEED_A  DC.B $00                        ; the deterministic maze
SEED_B  DC.B $00                        ;   generator state
DNG_LEVEL
        DC.B $00                        ; depth, 1-10
MON_BASE
        DC.B $00                        ; STR_MONSTERS base for
                                        ;   this level pair
MON_FREE
        HEX 00 00 00 00 00 00           ; 1 = kind in the pool
                                        ;   (slot 0 unused)
MON_X   HEX 00 00 00 00 00 00           ; monster columns
MON_Y   HEX 00 00 00 00 00 00           ; monster rows
MON_HP  HEX 00 00 00 00 00 00           ; hit points, low
MON_HP_HI
        HEX 00 00 00 00 00 00           ; hit points, high
VIEW_CELL
        DC.B $00                        ; feature at VIEW_DEPTH
VIEW_L  DC.B $00                        ; features beside it
VIEW_R  DC.B $00
VIEW_L_PREV
        DC.B $00                        ; same, previous depth
VIEW_R_PREV
        DC.B $00
