\section{MAPCHARS}
\label{sec:mapchars}

\texttt{MAPCHARS} --- the town and castle glyph bank: an alternate
\textbf{bank A} (128 glyphs $\times$ 8 scanlines, plane-major ---
the format is documented with [[FONT_BANK]] in the \texttt{STUPH}
chapter) that the \texttt{TWN} and \texttt{CAS} overlays load over
[[FONT_BANK]] at [[$0800]]. Its terrain-strip glyphs
([[$00]]--[[$19]]) become wall sections, doors and counters, and it
adds an \emph{inverse-video} capital alphabet --- the
\texttt{TCMAPS} map data embeds ASCII letters directly in its cell
codes to spell shop signs (\texttt{FOOD} is plainly visible in the
map bytes) and these glyphs render them. The text positions
[[$20]]--[[$2F]] are blank because town maps never put
punctuation on the floor.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/mapchars_font.png}
\caption{The \texttt{MAPCHARS} glyph bank, 128 glyphs in index
order. Wall and counter strips at the top; the inverse shop-sign
alphabet in the middle; a few special figures at the end.}
\label{fig:mapchars-font}
\end{figure}

