\section{TCMAPS}

\texttt{TCMAPS} is the town and castle map data --- 7660 bytes at
[[$4000]], loaded by [[TWN]] and [[CAS]]. It opens with
[[TCMAPS_DIR]], a directory of ten word pointers, then ten
764-byte maps. Each map is a $38\times18 = 684$-byte grid of
[[MAPCHARS]] glyph codes (the displayed cells; [[TWN]] prints each
cell's byte through the [[MAPCHARS]] font), followed by an 80-byte
NPC table ([[TCMAPS_META0]] and friends) that places the
shopkeepers, guards and townsfolk. The shop signs (``ARMOUR'',
``FOOD'', ``WEAPONRY'', ``THE PUB''$\ldots$) are spelled
directly into the cell grid as ASCII glyph codes.

The NPC table is five parallel 16-entry arrays --- type, column,
row, and a 16-bit hit-point value --- decoded in the \texttt{TWN}
section: [[TWN]] copies the chosen record into [[TOWN_MAP]] and
reads the arrays at [[NPC_TYPE]], [[NPC_X]], [[NPC_Y]] and
[[NPC_HP]]. A type of [[$FF]] is an empty slot. The ten maps are the
game's towns and castles; the place-to-map mapping (\texttt{PLR\_PLACE}
reduced mod $\$15$ then less $\$0D$) lives in [[OVERLAY_ENTRY]].

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{images/tcmaps_all.png}
\caption{The ten [[TCMAPS]] maps rendered through the
[[MAPCHARS]] font (renderer
\texttt{.claude/scripts/render\_tcmaps.py}). Towns with their
shops and a walled castle (top right, ``MESS HALL'' / ``PRISON''
/ ``STABLES''); the bottom strip of each tile is the 80-byte
NPC table shown as glyphs.}
\end{figure}

